name: Riverine Flood
headline: Moderate Flood Warning for Eyre Creek, Eyre Creek at Bedourie and Eyre Creek at Glengyle
description:
Moderate flooding is occurring along the Eyre Creek, with renewed rises possible as a flood peak travelling downstream.
Eyre Creek at Bedourie is currently at 4.53 metres and falling slowly, above the moderate flood level (4.00 m). Eyre Creek at Bedourie is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (4.00 m) for the next few days.No current river level observations are available for the Eyre Creek at Glengyle. The river level is estimated to be below the major flood level (4.00 m) and falling, with moderate flooding. The Eyre Creek at Glengyle is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (3.00 m) for the next few days, with renewed rises possible as an upstream flood peak arrive.
instruction:
Remember: If it's flooded, forget it. For flood emergency assistance contact the SES on 132 500. For life threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately.
Current emergency information is available at www.qld.gov.au/alerts

name: Riverine Flood
headline: Moderate Flood Warning for Warrego River (NSW), Warrego River at Barringun No. 2, Warrego River at Enngonia and Warrego River at Fords Bridge Bywash
description:
Moderate flooding is continuing along the Warrego River (NSW).
The Warrego River at Barringun No. 2 is currently at 4.13 metres and falling, above the moderate flood level (3.80 m). The Warrego River at Barringun No. 2 may fall below the moderate flood level (3.80 m) during Sunday.The Warrego River at Enngonia was at 2.58 metres and steady near a peak around 9:30 am Saturday, above the moderate flood level (2.50 m). The Warrego River at Enngonia may remain around 2.60 metres until Monday, with moderate flooding.The Warrego River at Fords Bridge Bywash is currently at 2.95 metres and rising slowly, above the moderate flood level (2.30 m). The Warrego River at Fords Bridge Bywash may peak around 3.00 metres late Saturday, with moderate flooding. Prolonged flooding is likely as floodwaters arrive from upstream.
instruction:
In life threatening emergencies, call 000 (triple zero) immediately. If you require rescue, assistance to evacuate or other emergency help, ring NSW SES on 132 500.
* Avoid drowning. Stay out of rising water, seek refuge in the highest available place.
* Prevent damage to your vehicle. Move it under cover, away from areas likely to flood.
* Avoid being swept away. Stay out of fast-flowing creeks and storm drains.
* Never drive, ride or walk through flood water. Flood water can be deceptive and dangerous.

For more emergency information, advice, and access to the latest river heights and rainfall observations and forecasts:

name: Riverine Flood
headline: Moderate Flood Warning for Cann River, Cann River (West) at Weeragua and Cann River (East) at Chandlers Creek
description:
Moderate flooding may occur along the Cann River.
The Cann River (West) at Weeragua is currently at 2.54 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Cann River (West) at Weeragua is likely to exceed the minor flood level (3.00 m) Tuesday evening. The river level may reach the moderate flood level (3.50 m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday. Further rises are possible with forecast rainfall.The Cann River (East) at Chandlers Creek is currently at 1.98 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The Cann River (East) at Chandlers Creek is likely to exceed the minor flood level (2.00 m) Tuesday afternoon. The river level may reach the moderate flood level (2.30 m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday. Further rises are possible with forecast rainfall.
instruction:
SES advises that all community members should:
Never walk, ride or drive through floodwater,
Never allow children to play in floodwater,
Stay away from waterways and stormwater drains during and after heavy rain,
Keep well clear of fallen power lines
Be aware that in fire affected areas, rainfall run-off into waterways may contain debris such as ash, soil, trees and rocks, and heavy rainfall increases the potential for landslides and debris across roads.

Current Emergency Information is available at www.emergency.vic.gov.au
For emergency assistance contact the SES on 132 500.
Current Road and Traffic Information is available at the VicRoads website: www.traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/

headline: Warning to Sheep Graziers for Snowy Mountains forecast district
